For example people say Gleam has 15 keywords which is probably true in some important technical sense, but doesn't count "_" underscore which maybe isn't exactly a keyword in that technical sense, but practically speaking you need to know to read Gleam case statements.

For instance https://forums.swift.org/t/where-can-i-get-the-full-list-of-swift-keywords/71488/29 maybe adding some keywords doesn't make the language more complex, or for instance Go making you use "for" to do a while loop doesn't simplify anything. Still...

I omitted keywords that are reserved for future use but don't do anything, because a) makes Gleam look better and b) when you read code in a language you don't need to know anything about keywords that don't do anything. I also didn't count operators like "==", "+", "||", etc., maybe people who do languages and compilers would have a more formal way of counting keywords . Or for example people always say oh Gleam has only 15 keywords...really imo "_" counts from a practical perspective, you need to know it matches anything in a case, but maybe it's different in some technical sense idk. Point is this is not really precise, imo when we talk about keywords we mean words, but my judgement is kind of made up.


